What is Data Skew?
Data is considered skewed when it is not evenly distributed across partitions. Skewed data can lead to performance issues such as straggler tasks, long-running stages, and inefficient resource utilization.
What is Salting?
Salting is a technique used to mitigate skewed joins in Spark.
In this approach, an additional column called a salt key is introduced to distribute skewed data across multiple partitions, thereby balancing the join workload.
Skewed Data Use Case
Assume the orders table is heavily skewed because customer_id = 5 alone contains more than 100 GB of data. A normal join on customer_id would result in severe skew and performance degradation.
Salting Example for customer and orders Tables
from pyspark.sql import functions as F
df = spark.range(4).alias("salt_key")
customer = spark.table("customer").crossJoin(df)
orders = (
spark.table("orders")
.withColumn("salt_key", (F.rand() * 4).cast("int"))
)
out = customer.join(
orders,
(orders.customer_id == customer.customer_id) &
(customer.salt_key == orders.salt_key),
"inner"
)
Adaptive Query Execution (AQE) for Skewed Joins
Spark’s Adaptive Query Execution (AQE) can automatically optimize skewed joins at runtime.
To enable skewed join optimization, the following configurations should be set to true: 
spark.sql.adaptive.forceOptimizeSkewedJoin = true
This adaptive rule optimizes skewed joins to avoid straggler tasks, even if it introduces extra shuffle.
Skew Detection Thresholds
spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.skewedPartitionThresholdInBytes = 256MB
A partition is considered skewed if its size exceeds this threshold.
spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.skewedPartitionFactor = 5
A partition is considered skewed if its size is more than 5× the median partition size.
Broadcast Join Optimization
By default, Spark performs a broadcast join when the table size is ≤ 10 MB.
In real‑world scenarios, tables are often much larger.
Increase Broadcast Join Threshold
spark.sql.autoBroadcastJoinThreshold = 1GB
Increase Broadcast Timeout for Large Tables
spark.sql.broadcastTimeout = 15000
⚠️ Broadcasting large tables can be expensive, so increasing the timeout helps prevent failures.
When dealing with large shuffles (joins or aggregations), adjust below property:
spark.sql.shuffle.partitions = 500
This controls the number of partitions created during shuffle operations.
Caching as a Performance Optimization
Caching is useful only when a DataFrame is reused multiple times.
✅ Correct Use of Cache
df = spark.table("employee")
df.filter("employee_id = 1")
df.filter("employee_id = 2")
Since df is reused, caching can improve performance.
❌ Issues When Cache Is Used Incorrectly
Disk spilling due to insufficient memory
Extra CPU overhead from serialization and deserialization
Best Practices: -
Ensure the DataFrame or table is used multiple times
Confirm there is sufficient executor memory available
Validate cache effectiveness using Cache Utilization Ratio in the Spark UI
